What is the area enclosed by the region defined by the equation $x^2+y^2+10x+24y=0$?
inference:
$$x^2+y^2+10x+24y=0\newline (x^2+10x+25)+(y^2+24y+144)=25+144\newline (x+5)^2+(y+12)^2=169\newline x+5=\pm 13\text{ and }y+12=\pm 13\newline x=-18,-2\text{ and }y=-26,-6$$

So the area of square is 

$$2\times (13)^2=2\times 169=\boxed{338}.$$
Final Answer: $\boxed{338}.$ I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: We complete the square on the quadratic in $x$ by adding $(10/2)^2=25$ to both sides, and complete the square on the quadratic in $y$ by adding $(24/2)^2=144$ to both sides. We have the equation  \[(x^2+10x+25)+(y^2+24y+144)=169 \Rightarrow (x+5)^2+(y+12)^2=169\]We see that this is the equation of a circle with center $(-5,-12)$ and radius 13. Thus, the area of the region enclosed by this circle is $\pi \cdot 13^2=\boxed{169\pi}$.

(x+5)^2&=169-(y+12)^2\\
x+5&=\pm\sqrt{169-(y+12)^2}\\
x&=-5\pm\sqrt{169-(y+12)^2}\\
\end{align*}
Since the side length of the square is $\sqrt{169}=13$, the maximum and minimum values of $x$ are $6$ and $-18$. Therefore, the area of the square is $2\cdot13^2=\boxed{338}$.
